programme.title: The Man Who Came to Dinner

programme.title: Holiday Affair

programme.title: In the Good Old Summertime

A musical remake of "The Shop Around the Corner," in which the setting was changed from a Budapest sundries shop.

programme.title: How to Steal a Million

programme.title: The Thomas Crown Affair

Michel Legrand's score was Oscar nominated, and the song "The Windmills of Your Mind" was named Best Song.

programme.title: The Hot Rock
programme.desc: A former jewel thief agrees to steal back from a museum a diamond that was taken in colonial times from an African village.

programme.title: Ocean's 11

Ol' Blue Eyes is Danny Ocean, a playboy who rounds up his old army buddies for a military-style heist in Vegas. The plan: Ring-a-ding in the New Year with a rip off of five casinos. Peter Lawford, Angie Dickinson, Richard Conte.

programme.title: Dollars
programme.desc: Warren Beatty and Goldie Hawn in a spoof about crooks robbing crooks, with a West German bank as the target. Richard Brooks directed on location in Hamburg, Bavaria and Scandinavia. Kessel: Gert Frobe. Attorney: Robert Webber. Sarge: Scott Brady. Candy Man: Arthur Brauss.

programme.title: Bringing Up Baby
programme.desc: Screwball comedy about a dog with a taste for dinosaur bones, a housebroken leopard named Baby, a madcap heiress who sets her cap for an absent-minded paleontologist, and a wacky menagerie of secondary characters.

programme.title: The Philadelphia Story
programme.desc: In this Best Picture nominee, Katharine Hepburn re-creates her Broadway role as a divorced society woman preparing for her wedding while fending off the advances of a magazine reporter and her ex-husband. Playwright Philip Barry's comedy of manners captures "the privileged class enjoying its privileges" and landed Donald Ogden Stewart a Best Screenplay Oscar and James Stewart a Best Actor award as the journalist.

programme.title: My Favorite Wife
programme.desc: A woman returns home to her husband and their children after being marooned on a desert island for seven years. But she has been declared legally dead, and he now has a second wife.

programme.title: Plymouth Adventure
programme.desc: Epic re-creation of the Pilgrims' turbulent voyage to the New World aboard the Mayflower, captained by a stubborn seaman who promises to reach his destination come hell, high water or any other obstacle. An Oscar winner for special effects.

programme.title: Ambush
programme.desc: A civilian scout riding with the U.S. cavalry in 1878 Arizona Territory attempts to track down a general's daughter who's been abducted by Apaches.

programme.title: Lafayette Escadrille

programme.title: M*A*S*H
programme.desc: A beloved, multi-Emmy-winning series about Army surgeons cutting up amid the Korean War. 'War is hell. So is TV,' said Larry Gelbart, who developed the series for TV from the 1970 Robert Altman film. ' 'M*A*S*H' and the medium,' Gelbart added, 'were made for each other.' For 11 years (10 in the Top 20), the show deftly blended sharp, thoughtful humor with moving scenes of dedicated, stressed doctors trying to save lives---while clinging to their own sanity---in a Mobile Army Surgical Hospital.

programme.title: Bonanza
programme.desc: Ben Cartwright and his three sons (by three wives) ride herd over the sprawling Ponderosa spread in 1860s Nevada in one of the most handsomely mounted and beloved series of all time. The first TV Western to be shown in color, it ran for 14 seasons; was the top-rated show for three of them (1964-65, '65-66 and '66-67); had a number of first-rank directors (including Robert Altman) work on some episodes; and inspired several 'Bonanza' TV-movies (none especially distinctive).

programme.title: Gunsmoke
programme.desc: This landmark adult Western centered on Marshal Matt Dillon of Dodge City. John Wayne turned down the lead, suggesting James Arness (who remained for its entire run). Originating on radio (with William Conrad as Dillon), it moved to TV in September 1955. Its popularity spawned a number of copycats, but none would enjoy the longevity (and few the consistent quality) of this classic.

programme.title: The Andy Griffith Show
programme.desc: Gentle humor and genuinely likable characters made Mayberry a beloved fixture on the TV landscape. A Top 10 hit throughout its eight-year run (it went out at No. 1), this low-key, down-home sitcom harkened back to a simpler time and place. Mayberry may be a state of mind, but the sunny optimism and simple virtues it represents have actually been set in stone--in a Raleigh, N.C., statue depicting Sheriff Andy Taylor and his son, Opie. '[The show's] central theme was love,' Griffith said.

programme.title: Everybody Loves Raymond
programme.desc: Ray Romano hit the sitcom stratosphere with this gem based on his stand-up routine. It's about a Long Island sportswriter and his intrusive parents, who live (in)conveniently across the street from him, his wife and their three children. Romano and costars Patricia Heaton, Doris Roberts, Peter Boyle and Brad Garrett were virtual Emmy-nomination machines and scored eight wins among them. Boyle alone, curiously, never took home the prize.

programme.title: M*A*S*H
programme.desc: A beloved, multi-Emmy-winning series about Army surgeons cutting up amid the Korean War. 'War is hell. So is TV,' said Larry Gelbart, who developed the series for TV from the 1970 Robert Altman film. ' 'M*A*S*H' and the medium,' Gelbart added, 'were made for each other.' For 11 years (10 in the Top 20), the show deftly blended sharp, thoughtful humor with moving scenes of dedicated, stressed doctors trying to save lives---while clinging to their own sanity---in a Mobile Army Surgical Hospital.

programme.title: Bonanza
programme.desc: Ben Cartwright and his three sons (by three wives) ride herd over the sprawling Ponderosa spread in 1860s Nevada in one of the most handsomely mounted and beloved series of all time. The first TV Western to be shown in color, it ran for 14 seasons; was the top-rated show for three of them (1964-65, '65-66 and '66-67); had a number of first-rank directors (including Robert Altman) work on some episodes; and inspired several 'Bonanza' TV-movies (none especially distinctive).

programme.title: Gunsmoke
programme.desc: This landmark adult Western centered on Marshal Matt Dillon of Dodge City. John Wayne turned down the lead, suggesting James Arness (who remained for its entire run). Originating on radio (with William Conrad as Dillon), it moved to TV in September 1955. Its popularity spawned a number of copycats, but none would enjoy the longevity (and few the consistent quality) of this classic.

programme.title: The Andy Griffith Show
programme.desc: Gentle humor and genuinely likable characters made Mayberry a beloved fixture on the TV landscape. A Top 10 hit throughout its eight-year run (it went out at No. 1), this low-key, down-home sitcom harkened back to a simpler time and place. Mayberry may be a state of mind, but the sunny optimism and simple virtues it represents have actually been set in stone--in a Raleigh, N.C., statue depicting Sheriff Andy Taylor and his son, Opie. '[The show's] central theme was love,' Griffith said.

programme.title: Diary of a Mad Black Woman
programme.desc: Tyler Perry wrote and stars in this lively mix of domestic drama, romance and blistering comedy. When her rich husband divorces her, a woman tries to piece together her life with help from her sassy, gun-toting granny (Perry, in drag). Perry also plays two other characters and based the script on his stage play.

programme.title: Tyler Perry's Meet the Browns
programme.desc: Writer-director Tyler Perry's fourth film is an uproarious, insightful comedy about a hard-luck single mom (Angela Bassett) from Chicago who attends her long-estranged father's funeral in rural Georgia and meets a clan of offbeat relatives she didn't know she had. Former NBA star Rick Fox costars as a college hoops coach who is romantically interested in Bassett. Perry costars as Joe and has a cameo as his recurring character, the larger-than-life matriarch, Madea.
